title: Performance Issues: Where is the memory optimization?
body:
I look into the code base and I have two questions. 
1. The project claims using Rust is because it's faster than Python. But it looks like it only happens in the simple algorithm as your team re-build such an algorithm in Rust, and for the transformer, the Rust will still call the Python module and the performance gained by Rust is gone. 
2. As for the memory optimization, when tune the transformer, it goes the following steps
  (1) `let dataset = snapshot.text_dataset();` in `src/orm/model.rs` will call snap.text_dataset function. 
  (2) the text_dataset function will call `let result = client.select(&self.select_sql(), None, None).unwrap();` This will retrieve all records in the database memory !!!!! which will have a huge influence on normal data usage, such as insert or read. Where the memory optimization come from?

title: Changed full_text search to use plainto_tsquery
pgml.embed as a function
body:
First of all this is an awesome project! Many thanks for your hard work. 
I've stumbled across one issue I cannot comprehend. 

So I've have a query for embeds
```sql
WITH query AS (
    SELECT pgml.embed('intfloat/e5-small-v2', 'foo bar?')::vector AS embedding
)
SELECT kb, tag
FROM cm_embeddings,
     query
ORDER BY cm_embeddings.embedding <-> query.embedding
LIMIT 10;
```
This query executes in around 1sec. 
If I wrap it in a function and call it, it takes 2min to execute :( 
This is on 200 rows of data. 

```sql
create or replace function query_embedding(phase varchar)
    returns TABLE
            (
                kb    varchar,
                model varchar
            )
as
$$
with query AS (
    SELECT pgml.embed('intfloat/e5-small-v2', phase)::vector AS embedding
)
SELECT kb, tag
FROM cm_embeddings,
     query
ORDER BY cm_embeddings.embedding <-> query.embedding
LIMIT 10
$$
    LANGUAGE SQL;

SELECT query_embedding('foo bar');
```


Is it recreating embedding for each row ?? 
In my case `phase` parameter has to be dynamic so I have to use make it somehow into a function I can expose  to internal API. 
Is there any other way I should be tackling this ?

title: ERROR:  syntax error at or near "NULL"
body:
Hello!

When following the [Quick Start w/ Docker](https://postgresml.org/docs/guides/setup/quick_start_with_docker) guide, I get the following error on start-up with Docker Compose:

```sh
ERROR:  syntax error at or near "NULL"
```

I suspect this is due to a syntax error in the regression testing code:

https://github.com/postgresml/postgresml/blob/8bbc08ffdfa8ae287d62c0b2007f4c11f10e5f8d/pgml-extension/src/orm/task.rs#L84

This line in `task.rs` is written:

```rust
"ORDER BY models.metrics->>'{}' {} NULL LAST",
```

If this is for PostgreSQL, I think this is the wrong syntax.  I think in PostgreSQL an `ORDER BY` clause should have the keywords `NULLS LAST` not `NULL LAST`.  The PostgreSQL docs seem to support this:

https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-select.html

I could be wrong, though.  Thanks!
Best,
David

title: trying to install the postgresql-pgml-14 package on debian bullseye or boondocks results in HTTP 403
body:
trying to extend the official PG image with this extension, rather than the CUDA image mentioned in the Dockerfile your repo, but it seems there is some sort of key in the CUDA base image that allows access to https://apt.postgresml.org. Even trying to access that URL in my browser gives me a 403 response page. The installation docs imply that there are no other requirements for getting the package installed, so I have been assuming it can be installed into a non-CUDA environment. If that is just not possible, then perhaps that needs to be mentioned in the docs.

Here's my Dockerfile, which is largely derived from yours (as of 2023-06-29)

```
FROM postgres:14-bullseye

ARG DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive
ARG PGML_VERSION=2.6.0
ENV TZ=Etc/UTC

WORKDIR /app
COPY --chown=postgres:postgres requirements.txt /app/requirements.txt
COPY --chown=postgres:postgres requirements-xformers.txt /app/requirements-xformers.txt

RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y curl \
    lsb-release \
    python3 \
    python3-pip \
    tzdata \
    wget \
    git \
    cmake \
    libpq-dev \
    libclang-dev \
    gnupg

RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y lsb-release && \
    echo "deb [trusted=yes] https://apt.postgresml.org $(lsb_release -cs) main" >> /etc/apt/sources.list && \
    cat /etc/apt/sources.list && \
    apt-get update && apt-get install -y postgresql-pgml-14

RUN pip3 install -r /app/requirements.txt && \
 pip3 install -r requirements-xformers.txt --no-dependencies

RUN cd /tmp && \
    git clone --branch v0.4.1 https://github.com/pgvector/pgvector.git && \
    cd pgvector && \
    make && \
    make install

COPY --chmod=755 setup.sql /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/
CMD ["postgres", "-c", "shared_preload_libraries='pgml'"]

COPY --chown=postgres:postgres entrypoint.sh /app/docker/
ENTRYPOINT ["/bin/bash", "/app/docker/entrypoint.sh"]
```

title: provided pgml.control doesn't work for postgres 12, although pgml listed compatible with pg 11 through 15
body:
When I attempted to install pgml.control into postgres 12 & load the extension [by following this documentation](https://postgresml.org/docs/guides/setup/v2/installation), I saw an error that indicated it was failing to load the extension due to 'unrecognized parameter "trusted"' in the pgml.control file. 

I was able to get past this issue by removing this line from the pgml.control file. Afterwards, I could load and use the extension in pg12.

pgml.control edited
```
comment = 'pgml:  Created by the PostgresML team'
default_version = '2.5.3'
module_pathname = '$libdir/pgml'
relocatable = false
superuser = true
schema = 'pgml'

```
I believe this is because the 'trusted' parameter for extension control files was not added until postgres 13 onwards.

full log line below, before i removed the 'trusted' parameter as shown above from pgml.control.

have a good one :+1: 

`````
postgres-multimodal-postgres-multimodal-1  |    CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgml
postgres-multimodal-liquibase-1            | 
postgres-multimodal-liquibase-1            | Unexpected error running Liquibase: Migration failed for changeset sql/00010_initial_database_setup.sql::raw::includeAll:
postgres-multimodal-liquibase-1            |      Reason: liquibase.exception.DatabaseException: ERROR: unrecognized parameter "trusted" in file "/usr/share/postgresql/12/extension/pgml.control" [Failed SQL: (0) ----------------
`

title: Ability to Interact with Cached Models through an API
body:
### Description

Currently, there is no direct way to interact with the cached models downloaded by PostgresML. For instance, when using HuggingFace models, they get stored in `/var/lib/postgresql/.cache`. Users might want to delete or even see what models have been downloaded. 

I spoke with Lev on Discord and he mentioned that there is no API exposed to work with the cached models directly. 

### Suggested Feature

It would be helpful to provide an API for users to list, delete, or otherwise manage the models cached by PostgresML. This would give more control to the users over the storage and management of models without having to manually intervene at the file system level.

### Use Case

1. Listing all downloaded models.
2. Deleting specific models that are no longer needed.
3. Potentially updating models.
4. Dealing with fine tuning models at some point
